Configuration Management (My Understanding)

Configuration Management is basically about managing servers automatically instead of doing everything manually.

In simple words, instead of logging into each server and setting things up one by one, we use tools to do it for us.

When we say "configuration", it includes:

* OS version (like Ubuntu version)
* Installed software (nginx, git, etc.)
* Security updates
* Users and permissions
* Services running on the server
* Application setup

---

Why Do We Need Configuration Management?

Before learning DevOps, servers were managed manually.

Example:
ssh server1
ssh server2
ssh server3

Then run commands on each server.

This approach has problems:

* Very slow
* Repetitive work
* High chance of mistakes
* Not scalable

I realized that managing even 2–3 servers manually is annoying, so managing 100+ servers is almost impossible.

---

How Cloud Made It More Important

Earlier companies had fewer servers.

Now with cloud:

* Number of servers increased a lot (100 → 1000+)
* Servers are created and deleted dynamically
* Microservices architecture increases server count
* Separate environments (Dev, Test, Prod)

So manual work is not practical anymore.

👉 That’s where automation comes in → Configuration Management

---

Tools Used for Configuration Management

There are multiple tools:

* Puppet → uses pull model
* Chef → uses pull model
* Salt → hybrid
* Ansible → push model (most popular)

---

Why I Learned Ansible

I found Ansible easier compared to others because:

* It uses push model (I control everything from my machine)
* It is agentless (no need to install anything on servers)
* Uses SSH (simple and already known)
* Uses YAML (easy to read and write)
* Works with both Linux and Windows

---

How Ansible Works (My Understanding)

My laptop (WSL Ubuntu) acts as Control Node.

From here, I connect to servers using SSH.

Then I run commands or playbooks, and Ansible applies changes on all servers automatically.

Flow:

Control Node (My Laptop)
|
| SSH
↓
Managed Nodes (AWS EC2 servs
Final Thought

Configuration Management helped me understand how real-world systems are managed.

It is not just about installing software, but about:

* Automation
* Consistency
* Scalability

This is a core concept in DevOps.
